  <h2>Camping Water Filtration Tips</h2>
  <p>Choosing the right filter is only half the equation. How you use it matters just as much:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Collect water from flowing sources:</strong> Moving water in streams and rivers is generally cleaner than stagnant ponds. Look for sources above campsites, not below them where contamination collects.</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-filter turbid water:</strong> If water is visibly murky, strain it through a bandana or coffee filter before running it through your filter straw. This prevents premature clogging and extends filter life significantly.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep your filter from freezing:</strong> In cold weather, sleep with your filter straw in your sleeping bag. Ice crystals can damage hollow fiber membranes, causing invisible cracks that let pathogens through. A compromised filter looks normal but offers no protection.</li>
    <li><strong>Backwash regularly:</strong> If your filter supports backwashing (like the NatureNova kit), do it after every heavy-use day. Reversing the flow clears trapped sediment and restores flow rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Dry filters before long-term storage:</strong> After your trip, remove the caps and let the filter air dry completely before storing. Damp filters stored in sealed bags can grow mold internally.</li>
  </ul>

